      "Process_Info": {
        "Process_Category": "Laser Powder Bed Fusion",
        "Process_Text": {
          "original": "The alloy was additively manufactured (AM) using the laser powder-bed fusion (LPBF, EOS M290) process. Powder feedstock was gas-atomized under nitrogen and sieved into 20-63 μm size range. Mechanical coupons were fabricated with their length aligned along the build direction (BD) under an Ar atmosphere using a laser power of 370 W, scanning speed of 1300 mm/s, hatch spacing of 0.21 mm, layer thickness of 30 μm, and a beam size of 83 μm. Stripe scanning strategy with a width of 10 mm and stripe-to-stripe overlap of 0.02 mm was used. Scan rotation angle of 67° was used between layers. The substrate temperature was 150°C during printing to minimize residual stress.",
          "simplified": "LPBF using EOS M290 with gas-atomized powder (20-63 μm). Substrate temp 150°C. Build direction aligned samples."
        },
        "Equipment": "EOS M290",
        "Key_Params": {
          "Laser_Power_W": 370.0,
          "Scanning_Speed_mm_s": 1300.0,
          "Hatch_Spacing_um": 210.0,
          "Layer_Thickness_um": 30.0,
          "Build_Plate_Temperature_K": 423.15
        }
      },
      "Microstructure_Info": {
        "Microstructure_Text": {
          "original": "The as-fabricated microstructure consists of elongated <001>Al and <101>Al grains aligned along the BD, spanning multiple melt pools. Fine, submicron-sized (Ce,Cu)-rich intermetallic particles distributed uniformly. APT analysis shows supersaturation of Zr (~0.4 wt.%) in the α-Al matrix. Ce, Fe, Sn are not in the α-Al matrix, having formed precipitates. The regions just above melt pool boundaries are devoid of (Ce,Cu)-rich particles. XRD reveals α-Al, Al8Cu4Ce, Al11Ce3, and Sn precipitates.",
          "simplified": "Elongated α-Al grains. Uniformly distributed submicron (Ce,Cu)-rich intermetallic particles. Zr is supersaturated in α-Al matrix (~0.4 wt.%)."
        },
